# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-mesos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Mesos began as a research project in the UC Berkeley RAD Lab by then PhD students Benjamin Hindman, Andy Konwinski, and Matei Zaharia, as well as professor Ion Stoica.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] The students started working on the project as part of a course taught by David Culler.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] It was originally named *Nexus* but due to a conflict with another university's project, was renamed to Mesos.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Mesos was first presented in 2009 (while still named Nexus) by Andy Konwinski at HotCloud '09 in a talk accompanying the first paper published about the project.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] In 2011 a more developed version was presented in a talk by Zaharia at the Usenix Symposium on Networked Systems Design and Implementation.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Specifically, he presented the paper on Mesos authored by Benjamin Hindman, Andy Konwinski Ali Ghodsi, Anthony D.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Joseph, Randy Katz, Scott Shenker, Ion Stoica and Zaharia himself.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] On July 27, 2016, the Apache Software Foundation announced version 1.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] It added the ability to centrally supply Docker, rkt and appc instances.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] On April 5, 2021, it was voted to move Mesos to the Apache Attic, however the vote was cancelled two days later due to increased interest.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] As of August 2025, this project was retired and placed into the attic October 2025.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] As such, all development on this project has ceased.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Mesos uses Linux cgroups to provide isolation for CPU, memory, I/O and file system.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Mesos is comparable to Google's Borg scheduler, a platform used internally to manage and distribute Google's services.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Apache Aurora is a Mesos framework for both long-running services and cron jobs, originally developed by Twitter starting in 2010 and open sourced in late 2013.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] It can scale to tens of thousands of servers, and holds many similarities to Borg including its rich domain-specific language (DSL) for configuring services.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] As of February 2020 the project was retired to the Attic.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] A fork of the project was maintained by former members, hosted on GitHub under the name Aurora Scheduler.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Chronos is a distributed cron-like system which is elastic and capable of expressing dependencies between jobs.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Marathon is promoted for platform as a service or container orchestration system scaling to thousands of physical servers.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] It is fully REST-based and allows canary-style deployments and deployment topologies.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] It is written in the programming language Scala.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] The social networking site Twitter began using Mesos and Apache Aurora in 2010, after Hindman gave a presentation to a group of Twitter engineers.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Airbnb said in July 2013 that it uses Mesos to run data processing systems like Apache Hadoop and Apache Spark.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] The Internet auction website eBay stated in April 2014 that it used Mesos to run continuous integration on a per-developer basis.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] They accomplish this by using a custom Mesos plugin that allows developers to launch their own private Jenkins instance.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] In April 2015, it was announced that Apple service Siri is using its own Mesos framework called Jarvis.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] In August 2015, it was announced that Verizon selected Mesosphere's DC/OS, which is based on open source Apache Mesos, for data center service orchestration.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] In November 2015, Yelp announced they had been using Mesos and Marathon for a year and a half for production services.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] Software startup Mesosphere, Inc. sells the Datacenter Operating System, a distributed operating system, based on Apache Mesos.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] In September 2015, Microsoft announced a commercial partnership with Mesosphere to build container scheduling and orchestration services for Microsoft Azure.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-mesos] In October 2015, Oracle announced support for Mesos through Oracle Container Cloud Service.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper is essentially a service for distributed systems offering a hierarchical key-value store, which is used to provide a distributed configuration service, synchronization service, and naming registry for large distributed systems (see *Use cases*).
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper was a sub-project of Hadoop but is now a top-level Apache project in its own right.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper's architecture supports high availability through redundant services.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] Clients can ask another ZooKeeper leader if the first fails to answer.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper nodes store their data in a hierarchical name space, like a file system or a tree data structure.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] Clients can read from and write to the nodes and in this way have a shared configuration service.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper can be viewed as an atomic broadcast system, through which updates are totally ordered.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] The ZooKeeper Atomic Broadcast (ZAB) protocol is the core of the system.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper is used by companies including Yelp, Rackspace, Yahoo, Odnoklassniki, Reddit, NetApp SolidFire, Meta, Twitter and eBay as well as open source enterprise search systems like Solr and distributed database systems like Apache Pinot.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper is modeled after Google's Chubby lock service and was originally developed at Yahoo! for streamlining the processes running on big-data clusters by storing the status in local log files on the ZooKeeper servers.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] These servers communicate with client machines to deliver the required information.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] ZooKeeper was developed to address issues that emerged during the deployment of distributed big-data applications.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] The services in the cluster are replicated and stored on a set of servers (called an "ensemble"), each of which maintains an in-memory database containing the entire data tree of state as well as a transaction log and snapshots stored persistently.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] Multiple client applications can connect to a server, and each client maintains a TCP connection through which it sends requests and heartbeats and receives responses and watch events for monitoring.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] In addition to the client libraries included with the ZooKeeper distribution, several third-party libraries, including Apache Curator and Kazoo, extend ZooKeeper's capabilities.
[src:apache-mesos/apache-zookeeper] These libraries offer enhanced ease of use, additional features and support for a broader range of programming languages.
[src:apache-mesos/cluster-manager] Within cluster and parallel computing, a **cluster manager** is usually backend graphical user interface (GUI) or command-line interface (CLI) software that runs on a set of cluster nodes that it manages (in some cases it runs on a different server or cluster of management servers).
[src:apache-mesos/cluster-manager] The cluster manager works together with a cluster management agent.
[src:apache-mesos/cluster-manager] These agents run on each node of the cluster to manage and configure services, a set of services, or to manage and configure the complete cluster server itself (see supercomputing.) In some cases the cluster manager is mostly used to dispatch work for the cluster (or cloud) to perform.
[src:apache-mesos/cluster-manager] In this last case a subset of the cluster manager can be a remote desktop application that is used not for configuration but just to send work and get back work results from a cluster.
[src:apache-mesos/cluster-manager] In other cases the cluster is more related to availability and load balancing than to computational or specific service clusters.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:apache-mesos/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The **mesosphere** (/ˈmɛsəsfɪər, ˈmɛz-, ˈmiːsə-, -zə-/; from Ancient Greek μέσος*(*mésos*)* 'middle' and *-sphere*) is the third layer of the atmosphere, directly above the stratosphere and directly below the thermosphere.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] In the mesosphere, temperature decreases as altitude increases.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] This characteristic is used to define limits,: it begins at the top of the stratosphere (sometimes called the stratopause), and ends at the mesopause, which is the coldest part of Earth's atmosphere, with temperatures below −143 °C (−225 °F; 130 K).
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The stratosphere and mesosphere are sometimes collectively referred to as the "middle atmosphere", which spans altitudes approximately between 12 and 80 km (7.5 and 49.7 mi) above Earth's surface.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The mesopause, at an altitude of 80–90 km (50–56 mi), separates the mesosphere from the thermosphere—the second-outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] On Earth, the mesopause nearly co-incides with the turbopause, below which different chemical species are well-mixed due to turbulent eddies.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Above this level the atmosphere becomes non-uniform because the scale heights of different chemical species differ according to their molecular masses.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The term *near space* is also sometimes used to refer to altitudes within the mesosphere.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Some sources distinguish between the terms "near space" and "upper atmosphere", so that only the layers closest to the Kármán line are described as "near space".
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Within the mesosphere, temperature decreases with increasing height.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] This is a result of decreasing absorption of solar radiation by the rarefied atmosphere having a diminishing relative ozone concentration as altitude increases (ozone being the main absorber in the UV wavelengths that survived absorption by the thermosphere).
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Additionally, this is also a result of increasing cooling by CO2 radiative emission.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The top of the mesosphere, called the mesopause, is the coldest part of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Temperatures in the upper mesosphere fall as low as about −100 °C (173 K; −148 °F), varying according to latitude and season.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The main most important features in this region are strong zonal (east-west) winds, atmospheric tides, internal atmospheric gravity waves (commonly called "gravity waves"), and planetary waves.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Most of these tides and waves start in the troposphere and lower stratosphere, and propagate to the mesosphere.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] In the mesosphere, gravity-wave amplitudes can become so large that the waves become unstable and dissipate.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] This dissipation deposits momentum into the mesosphere and largely drives global circulation.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Noctilucent clouds are located in the mesosphere.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The upper mesosphere is also the region of the ionosphere known as the *D layer*, which is only present during the day when some ionization occurs with nitric oxide being ionized by Lyman series-alpha hydrogen radiation.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The ionization is so weak that when night falls, and the source of ionization is removed, the free electron and ion form back into a neutral molecule.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Made of unbound, non-ionized atoms of sodium, the sodium layer radiates weakly to contribute to the airglow.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The sodium has an average concentration of 400,000 atoms per cubic centimetre.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] This band is regularly replenished by sodium sublimating from incoming meteors.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Astronomers have begun utilizing this sodium band to create "guide stars" as part of the adaptive optical correction process used to produce ultra-sharp ground-based observations.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Other metal layers, e.g. iron and potassium, exist in the upper mesosphere/lower thermosphere region as well.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Beginning in October 2018, a distinct type of aurora has been identified, originating in the mesosphere.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Often referred to as 'dunes' due to their resemblance to sandy ripples on a beach, the green undulating lights extend toward the equator.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] They have been identified as originating about 96 km (60 mi; 315,000 ft) above the surface.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Since auroras are caused by ultra-high-speed solar particles interacting with atmospheric molecules, the green color of these dunes has tentatively been explained by the interaction of those solar particles with oxygen molecules.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The dunes therefore occur where mesospheric oxygen is more concentrated.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Millions of meteors enter the Earth's atmosphere, averaging 40,000 tons per year.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The ablated material, called meteoric smoke, is thought to serve as condensation nuclei for noctilucent clouds.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The mesosphere lies above altitude records for aircraft, while only the lowest few kilometers are accessible to balloons, for which the altitude record is 53.0 kilometres (32.9 mi).
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] Meanwhile, the mesosphere is below the minimum altitude for orbital spacecraft due to high atmospheric drag.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] It has only been accessed through the use of sounding rockets, which are only capable of taking mesospheric measurements for a few minutes per mission.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] As a result, it is the least-understood part of the atmosphere, resulting in the humorous moniker *ignorosphere*.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] The presence of red sprites and blue jets (electrical discharges or lightning within the lower mesosphere), noctilucent clouds, and density shears within this poorly understood layer are of current scientific interest.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] On February 1, 2003, Space Shuttle *Columbia* broke up on reentry at about 62 km (39 mi) altitude, in the lower mesosphere, killing all seven crew members.
[src:apache-mesos/mesosphere] In 2025 scientists proposed photophoretic sunlight-powered flying structures for sustained exploration of the mesosphere, with potential applications in atmospheric sensing, communications, and exploration of thin-atmosphere planets such as Mars.
[src:apache-mesos/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:apache-mesos/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:apache-mesos/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:apache-mesos/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:apache-mesos/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:apache-mesos/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:apache-mesos/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:apache-mesos/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:apache-mesos/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
